<tr><td></td><td>TEASER</td></tr>
<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Shuttlepod</td></tr>
<tr id="L1"><td><a href="#L1">1</a></td><td>REED:  The Captain said they'd be mapping this asteroid field, but I can't see head nor tails of them.</td></tr>

<tr id="L2"><td><a href="#L2">2</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Maybe it's another asteroid field.</td></tr>

<tr id="L3"><td><a href="#L3">3</a></td><td>REED:  No, this is the one. Two primaries, seventeen planetesimals.</td></tr>

<tr id="L4"><td><a href="#L4">4</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Tucker is examining a circuit with a laser.</td></tr>

<tr id="L5"><td><a href="#L5">5</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Well, they weren't expecting us back for three days. Maybe they finished and went off to do something else.</td></tr>

<tr id="L6"><td><a href="#L6">6</a></td><td>REED:  Well, with our sensor array down, we won't know when they get back until we see them. Any luck with the comm?</td></tr>

<tr id="L7"><td><a href="#L7">7</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Dead as a doornail. I don't understand it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L8"><td><a href="#L8">8</a></td><td>REED:  Well, no doubt you'll have your boys take this pod apart piece by piece once it's back in the launch bay.</td></tr>

<tr id="L9"><td><a href="#L9">9</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I'd feel a lot more comfortable having everything in working order by the time Enterprise gets back.</td></tr>

<tr id="L10"><td><a href="#L10">10</a></td><td>REED:  Well, tinker all you like. I've got a copy of Ulysses here. I doubt I'll even be halfway through it by the time the ship gets back.</td></tr>

<tr id="L11"><td><a href="#L11">11</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I'd rather realign every micro-circuit on this shuttle than try to wade through that baby.</td></tr>

<tr id="L12"><td><a href="#L12">12</a></td><td>REED:  British schools have a core curriculum. It serves to provide a well-rounded education. Sometimes I think you North Americans read nothing but comic books and those ridiculous science fiction novels.</td></tr>

<tr id="L13"><td><a href="#L13">13</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I'll have you know that Superman was laced with metaphor. Subtext layered on subtext.</td></tr>

<tr id="L14"><td><a href="#L14">14</a></td><td>REED:  Oh, if only Doctor Cochrane had been a European. The Vulcans would have been far less reticent to help us. But, no, he had to be from Montana. He probably spent his nights reading about cowboys and Indians.</td></tr>

<tr id="L15"><td><a href="#L15">15</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Well, I don't recall any Europeans figuring out how to build a warp engine.</td></tr>

<tr id="L16"><td><a href="#L16">16</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Reed is looking out the main window.</td></tr>

<tr id="L17"><td><a href="#L17">17</a></td><td>REED:  Commander.</td></tr>

<tr id="L18"><td><a href="#L18">18</a></td><td>TUCKER:  No Brits, no Italians, no Serbo-Croatians.</td></tr>

<tr id="L19"><td><a href="#L19">19</a></td><td>REED:  Commander. I think you'd better come and take a look at this.</td></tr>

<tr id="L20"><td><a href="#L20">20</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: They are passing an asteroid with a big crash site on it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L21"><td><a href="#L21">21</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Bring us in closer.</td></tr>

<tr id="L22"><td><a href="#L22">22</a></td><td>REED:  Is it a ship?</td></tr>

<tr id="L23"><td><a href="#L23">23</a></td><td>TUCKER:  If the damn sensors were only working, we could. Bring us around again. There. Slow down.</td></tr>

<tr id="L24"><td><a href="#L24">24</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: The sight of a piece of metal with 01 on it brings a lump to their throats</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Ready room</td></tr>
<tr id="L25"><td><a href="#L25">25</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Come in. How are the Tesnians doing?</td></tr>

<tr id="L26"><td><a href="#L26">26</a></td><td>HOSHI:  Dr. Phlox can only keep twelve of them in the Decon chamber at a time.</td></tr>

<tr id="L27"><td><a href="#L27">27</a></td><td>ARCHER:  What about the other, what is it, twenty two?</td></tr>

<tr id="L28"><td><a href="#L28">28</a></td><td>HOSHI:  He's rotating them. They seem to be doing fine on our atmosphere but they need at least six hours of boron gas a day. He says we've got enough to get them home.</td></tr>

<tr id="L29"><td><a href="#L29">29</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Have you learned their language?</td></tr>

<tr id="L30"><td><a href="#L30">30</a></td><td>HOSHI:  Yes, sir.</td></tr>

<tr id="L31"><td><a href="#L31">31</a></td><td>ARCHER:  What do they have to say?</td></tr>

<tr id="L32"><td><a href="#L32">32</a></td><td>HOSHI:  They're pretty rattled. Most of them have been on that ship for years. It's a lot to digest they lost everything.</td></tr>

<tr id="L33"><td><a href="#L33">33</a></td><td>ARCHER:  They're alive. Does the Captain have any idea what happened?</td></tr>

<tr id="L34"><td><a href="#L34">34</a></td><td>HOSHI:  No, and he feels terrible about the damage to Enterprise. He has no idea what went wrong. When they approached our docking port they lost control of their sensor array, and then a few seconds later their navigation system went out.</td></tr>

<tr id="L35"><td><a href="#L35">35</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Thank God their escape pods were working.</td></tr>

<tr id="L36"><td><a href="#L36">36</a></td><td>HOSHI:  I saw the wreckage on the asteroid. There wasn't much left.</td></tr>

<tr id="L37"><td><a href="#L37">37</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Archer to Mayweather. What's our ETA?</td></tr>

<tr id="L38"><td><a href="#L38">38</a></td><td>TRAVIS [OC]:  We should reach Tesnia in about twenty hours, sir.</td></tr>

<tr id="L39"><td><a href="#L39">39</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Good work. That should get us back to our rendezvous co-ordinates well before Trip and Malcolm get there. Let's drop out of warp for a few minutes. I want to inspect the damage to the launch doors.</td></tr>

<tr id="L40"><td><a href="#L40">40</a></td><td>TRAVIS:  Aye, sir.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Inspection pod</td></tr>
<tr id="L41"><td><a href="#L41">41</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Smaller and rounder than a shuttlepod, with no wings for atmosphere flight.</td></tr>

<tr id="L42"><td><a href="#L42">42</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Who's in charge of Engineering while Trip's away?</td></tr>

<tr id="L43"><td><a href="#L43">43</a></td><td>T'POL:  Lieutenant Hess.</td></tr>

<tr id="L44"><td><a href="#L44">44</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Tell her to get a team working on a new starboard door for launch bay two.</td></tr>

<tr id="L45"><td><a href="#L45">45</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: They glide underneath the gaping hole and twisted metal where the launch door used to be.</td></tr>

<tr id="L46"><td><a href="#L46">46</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Everything else check out all right?</td></tr>

<tr id="L47"><td><a href="#L47">47</a></td><td>T'POL:  Astrometrics detected what could be micro-singularities in the vicinity of the asteroid field.</td></tr>

<tr id="L48"><td><a href="#L48">48</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Micro-singularities are a Vulcan myth. There's no scientific evidence that they exist.</td></tr>

<tr id="L49"><td><a href="#L49">49</a></td><td>T'POL:  Our deflectors registered some unusual charged particles at the same time the Tesnian ship began to malfunction.</td></tr>

<tr id="L50"><td><a href="#L50">50</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Any similar damage on Enterprise?</td></tr>

<tr id="L51"><td><a href="#L51">51</a></td><td>T'POL:  No, but our hull plating was polarised.</td></tr>

<tr id="L52"><td><a href="#L52">52</a></td><td>ARCHER:  Micro-singularities. If the Vulcans had their way they'd blame them for the common cold.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Shuttlepod</td></tr>
<tr id="L53"><td><a href="#L53">53</a></td><td>TUCKER:  How about the lifeboats? They could have launched the lifeboats before the crash.</td></tr>

<tr id="L54"><td><a href="#L54">54</a></td><td>REED:  They'd be here. They only go three hundred kph. They'd be right here waiting for us to return.</td></tr>

<tr id="L55"><td><a href="#L55">55</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Are we sure there are no survivors?</td></tr>

<tr id="L56"><td><a href="#L56">56</a></td><td>REED:  Commander, we have to figure out what we're going to do.</td></tr>

<tr id="L57"><td><a href="#L57">57</a></td><td>TUCKER:  We can't just leave. That's Enterprise. At least we should find the black boxes.</td></tr>

<tr id="L58"><td><a href="#L58">58</a></td><td>REED:  With what? We have no radio. Nothing to pick up the beacons.</td></tr>

<tr id="L59"><td><a href="#L59">59</a></td><td>TUCKER:  What's the range in our distress beacon?</td></tr>

<tr id="L60"><td><a href="#L60">60</a></td><td>REED:  It's offline.</td></tr>

<tr id="L61"><td><a href="#L61">61</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I'm talking about the portable one. The one in the away kit.</td></tr>

<tr id="L62"><td><a href="#L62">62</a></td><td>REED:  Ten million kilometers, maybe twenty, but I highly doubt there'd be a ship anywhere close to that.</td></tr>

<tr id="L63"><td><a href="#L63">63</a></td><td>TUCKER:  We've only got ten days worth of breathable air. How far to Echo Three?</td></tr>

<tr id="L64"><td><a href="#L64">64</a></td><td>REED:  At impulse? A lot more than ten days.</td></tr>

<tr id="L65"><td><a href="#L65">65</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Well, if we could get close enough for it to pick up our distress beacon it'd relay the signal back to Starfleet.</td></tr>

<tr id="L66"><td><a href="#L66">66</a></td><td>REED:  I'm afraid the math doesn't work out, Commander. It's going to take weeks, maybe months for our signal to reach Echo Three. By the time Starfleet got a ship out here we'd be, we'd be long dead.</td></tr>

<tr id="L67"><td><a href="#L67">67</a></td><td>TUCKER:  But at least they'd find us. They'd get their shuttlepod back, a couple of well-preserved corpses.</td></tr>

<tr id="L68"><td><a href="#L68">68</a></td><td>REED:  Sir.</td></tr>

<tr id="L69"><td><a href="#L69">69</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Which way?</td></tr>

<tr id="L70"><td><a href="#L70">70</a></td><td>REED:  Which way to what?</td></tr>

<tr id="L71"><td><a href="#L71">71</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Echo Three. Which way to Echo Three?</td></tr>

<tr id="L72"><td><a href="#L72">72</a></td><td>REED:  I told you, it's too far.</td></tr>

<tr id="L73"><td><a href="#L73">73</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Do you know which direction it is or don't you?</td></tr>

<tr id="L74"><td><a href="#L74">74</a></td><td>REED:  Navigation is down.</td></tr>

<tr id="L75"><td><a href="#L75">75</a></td><td>TUCKER:  That's not what I asked you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L76"><td><a href="#L76">76</a></td><td>REED:  You want me to guess?</td></tr>

<tr id="L77"><td><a href="#L77">77</a></td><td>TUCKER:  You come from a long line of Navy men and you got a real good memory. Look hard at those stars, find something that looks familiar and tell me which way to go.</td></tr>

<tr id="L78"><td><a href="#L78">78</a></td><td>REED:  Sir.</td></tr>

<tr id="L79"><td><a href="#L79">79</a></td><td>TUCKER:  That's an order!</td></tr>

<tr id="L80"><td><a href="#L80">80</a></td><td>REED:  I don't suppose you have a sextant handy.</td></tr>

<tr id="L81"><td><a href="#L81">81</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I left it with my slide rule. (Reed sits in the pilot's seat) Well?</td></tr>

<tr id="L82"><td><a href="#L82">82</a></td><td>REED:  That blue giant, we may have gone by it. I'm not sure.</td></tr>

<tr id="L83"><td><a href="#L83">83</a></td><td>TUCKER:  That's good enough for me. Take one more low pass over the wreckage and then set a course.</td></tr>

<tr id="L84"><td><a href="#L84">84</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: They swoop down over the 01 sign.</td></tr>

<tr id="L85"><td><a href="#L85">85</a></td><td>TUCKER:  See you around, Captain.</td></tr>

<tr id="L86"><td><a href="#L86">86</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Later- </td></tr>

<tr id="L87"><td><a href="#L87">87</a></td><td>REED:  Personal log, Lieutenant Malcolm Reed. November 9, 2151. By the time anyone hears this, by anyone, I suppose I mean anyone human, Commander Tucker and I will be long dead. It's my intention to recount the events that led to the destruction of the Starship Enterprise and to express my deepest feelings regarding my short but memorable service with Starfleet.</td></tr>

<tr id="L88"><td><a href="#L88">88</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Tell them I'd love to add my two cents, but I'm trying to get a little work done.</td></tr>

<tr id="L89"><td><a href="#L89">89</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Reed rewinds a little.</td></tr>

<tr id="L90"><td><a href="#L90">90</a></td><td>REED:  [OC] short but memorable service with Starfleet.</td></tr>

<tr id="L91"><td><a href="#L91">91</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He resumes dictation.</td></tr>

<tr id="L92"><td><a href="#L92">92</a></td><td>REED:  In order to test the targeting scanners on Shuttlepod one, Commander Tucker and I had to get at least twenty thousand kilometres from Enterprise. During our third trial, we experienced a brief but sizable jolt, and shortly thereafter realised that our sensor array had gone offline.</td></tr>

<tr id="L93"><td><a href="#L93">93</a></td><td>TUCKER:  This sensor array is more than offline. It's totally fried.</td></tr>

<tr id="L94"><td><a href="#L94">94</a></td><td>REED:  (rewinds) that our sensor array had gone offline. (resumes) We had no choice but to head back to the asteroid field where Enterprise was involved in a mapping project. We found the ship destroyed, its debris strewn across a square kilometre of one of the larger asteroids. Had our sensors been working we certainly would have done everything possible to determine the cause of the disaster, but as it was, with only a short-range distress beacon and limited air, we had no alternative but to set a course for Echo Three where someday this vessel and eventually this log, will be found. May God have mercy on our souls.</td></tr>

<tr id="L95"><td><a href="#L95">95</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Why don't you cut the crap and get back here and help me?</td></tr>

<tr id="L96"><td><a href="#L96">96</a></td><td>REED:  What would you like me to do?</td></tr>

<tr id="L97"><td><a href="#L97">97</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I don't know. You could hold this flashlight, or turn down the heat. Whatever you want. I'm just getting a little tired of listening to all your pessimism.</td></tr>

<tr id="L98"><td><a href="#L98">98</a></td><td>REED:  If there's something you need me to do I would be more than happy to comply, but I'm afraid pessimism is simply not an accurate description of my log entry. I'm just being realistic, Commander.</td></tr>

<tr id="L99"><td><a href="#L99">99</a></td><td>TUCKER:  We've got nine days. We're bound to find someone out here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L100"><td><a href="#L100">100</a></td><td>REED:  At warp, perhaps, but at impulse?</td></tr>

<tr id="L101"><td><a href="#L101">101</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Vulcans, Klingons, Suliban, Xyrillians, Andorians. God knows who's going to be lurking around the next planet we run into.</td></tr>

<tr id="L102"><td><a href="#L102">102</a></td><td>REED:  But that's just it, sir. At impulse, we're not likely to be running into any planets. Not for at least six or seven years.</td></tr>

<tr id="L103"><td><a href="#L103">103</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Then somebody can run into us. You ever think of that? Or see us on their sensors. The possibilities are endless.</td></tr>

<tr id="L104"><td><a href="#L104">104</a></td><td>REED:  I'll heat up some rations. Unless of course you'd rather wait until we run into a vessel serving proper meals.</td></tr>

<tr id="L105"><td><a href="#L105">105</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Rations will be fine.</td></tr>

