<tr id="L111"><td><a href="#L111">111</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Any meat loaf?</td></tr>

<tr id="L112"><td><a href="#L112">112</a></td><td>REED:  With gravy and mashed potatoes.</td></tr>

<tr id="L113"><td><a href="#L113">113</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Perfect.</td></tr>

<tr id="L114"><td><a href="#L114">114</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Reed finds a bottle stashed in the cubby hole, too.</td></tr>

<tr id="L115"><td><a href="#L115">115</a></td><td>REED:  Kentucky bourbon.</td></tr>

<tr id="L116"><td><a href="#L116">116</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Yeah, the Captain was planning to give that to somebody. Can't remember who. Guess it's ours now.</td></tr>

<tr id="L117"><td><a href="#L117">117</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Reed puts the meals into the heater, and a couple of seconds later they are eating hot food from plastic trays.</td></tr>

<tr id="L118"><td><a href="#L118">118</a></td><td>TUCKER:  What's that?</td></tr>

<tr id="L119"><td><a href="#L119">119</a></td><td>REED:  The sea bass.</td></tr>

<tr id="L120"><td><a href="#L120">120</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Any good?</td></tr>

<tr id="L121"><td><a href="#L121">121</a></td><td>REED:  It's lovely. Thank you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L122"><td><a href="#L122">122</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Later again, Trip is trying to sleep but Reed is still doing dictation.</td></tr>

<tr id="L123"><td><a href="#L123">123</a></td><td>REED:  Captain Archer claims you told him you weren't even aware that I was serving on Enterprise. I find that difficult to believe, considering I wrote you twice in the weeks prior to our departure. Now, it is possible that you never received those letters. You were, I believe, in the process of moving back to Malaysia at the time. But you must have spoken to Aunt Sherry during that period, and I know she received my letters. I would hate to go to my death thinking that either of you felt I was trying to avoid</td></tr>

<tr id="L124"><td><a href="#L124">124</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Malcolm! You've been at it for hours now. Don't you think it's time to give it a rest?</td></tr>

<tr id="L125"><td><a href="#L125">125</a></td><td>REED:  As I'm sure you must have heard that was my esteemed colleague, Commander Charles Tucker. Mister Tucker doesn't share my belief that it is essential to say what must be said, to leave a record, tie up loose ends. Mister Tucker is labouring under the false hope that we are going to be miraculously rescued before we both suffocate.</td></tr>

<tr id="L126"><td><a href="#L126">126</a></td><td>TUCKER:  Mister and Mrs. Reed, I realise that you've just begun a period of mourning and that I'll never get an answer to this question, but I got to ask it anyway. Was Malcolm always this cynical?</td></tr>

<tr id="L127"><td><a href="#L127">127</a></td><td>REED:  In a few days, when the reality of this situation actually begins to sink in, you might very well decide you want to record some logs of your own. You have my word, I will not interrupt you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L128"><td><a href="#L128">128</a></td><td>TUCKER:  I just need to get some sleep, Malcolm! Is that so hard to understand?</td></tr>

<tr id="L129"><td><a href="#L129">129</a></td><td>REED:  We have less than nine days of oxygen left. It seems a waste to use it up sleeping.</td></tr>

<tr id="L130"><td><a href="#L130">130</a></td><td>TUCKER:  If I don't waste some oxygen sleeping, I'm going to start getting real cranky, and you don't want to spend your last nine days cooped up with me when I'm cranky. So turn that thing off and get some rest.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Sickbay</td></tr>
<tr id="L131"><td><a href="#L131">131</a></td><td>REED:  We're back.</td></tr>

<tr id="L132"><td><a href="#L132">132</a></td><td>PHLOX:  Lie still, Lieutenant.</td></tr>

